        "description": "YANGCHEN LHAMO | ThimphuThe Phensem Parents Support Group oriented parents, teachers, and Special Education Needs (SEN) Aides to help non-vocal children who are often addressed as Children with Disabilities (CwDs), with alternative…",
        "content": "| The Phensem Parents Support Group oriented parents, teachers, and Special Education Needs (SEN) Aides to help non-vocal children who are often addressed as Children with Disabilities (CwDs), with alternative modes of communication on 6 May. According to Phensem, many individuals, especially children with autism, are unable to communicate using speech and sound the way most other people do. However, this disability does not necessarily have to limit them from communicating their thoughts and emotions. Organizers said not being able to speak is not a deciding factor in the level of functioning. People with autism possess depth and wisdom, but we do not give them a voice, as per the autism supporting group. Thus the Phensem group conducted a training on “Alternative Modes of Communication” for parents, teachers, and SEN Aides in Thimphu to promote inclusiveness. The training was part of series of four training workshops with focus on four important domains that were identified in the field of inclusive learning and play, and was targeted for parents, teachers, and SEN Aides. Behavior management and positive reinforcement, inclusive play, alternative modes of communication, and technology as an assistive tool for learning for children with disabilities are the four domains. Karma Sonam Dorji, the Co-Founder and Executive Director of Phensem, said the training was conducted as access to learning in schools has been a challenge for children with disabilities who lack the motor skills to read and write the conventional way or even have speech and language issues. “Therefore, the training was to introduce alternative methods and pathways and the use of technology that can be provided to the children to assist them in learning and communicating in school or at home,” Karma said. Karma added that the impact on parents and teachers comes from how to carry out basic assessments to check the current level of communication of the children, how to set up strategy plans, and goal-setting in terms of how to help improve communication skills through different modes of communication. Overall, it is also to introduce augmentative and alternative communication skills. The Dzongkha teacher of Early Learning Center, Yonten Ngedrup, said that equal education opportunity is a basic human right and there is a need for inclusive SEN Aides in all schools. As of now, he pointed out that SEN Aides are only in selective schools. He suggests that if it can be provided in all schools, providing training not only to SEN teachers but even to other selected teachers. This is not to send SEN children to a particular school which is inconvenient for some. The dzongkhag teacher said that non-vocal children in Bhutan are left behind as compared to other countries. He said that training in alternative modes of communication will help CwDs access technologies to improve their communication. The parent of a child with autism, Wangmo, said the training has helped both parents and children communicate. However, she said that aid kits are not available in Bhutan and should be imported from third countries. She said if taxes for imported SEN Aides tools are reduced or waived off if possible. Wangmo usually imports toys from Sri Lanka. About 26 teachers, 10 parents and six SEN aides participated in the training. It is anticipated that about 416 children with disabilities will benefit, according to Phensem. The training was provided by ACC educators from the Communication Department of Vidya Sagar, India. These capacity buildings are supported by the Rotary Club of Thimphu.",
