    "video_url": null,
    "description": "Drops by 57 places from 33 among 180 countries according to the 2023 World Press Freedom Index YANGCHEN LHAMO | ThimphuBhutan has ranked 90th in the World Press Freedom Index this year,…",
    "content": "| Bhutan has ranked 90th in the World Press Freedom Index this year, a drop from previous year’s position of 33. This is according to the 2023 World Press Freedom Index (WPFI) compiled by the France-based organization Reporters Without Borders (RSF). The score is based on political, economic, legislative, social, and security indicators. Problems such as direct appointment of members of media regulatory body by the government, difficulties in getting access to state-held information, and self-censorship by journalists in the country are some of the factors that have attributed to the drop in the ranking. The report states that the country’s daily newspaper, , which is published in both English and Dzongkha, is owned by the government while there are six private newspapers. Private newspapers emerged as a transition to democracy since 2006. The , is a state-owned lone television in the country. Bhutan’s internet is now expanding fast, with more and more news and information circulating on blogs and social media. Current media scenario in the country is that some private houses have shut down over the years. More than 80 journalists, including 20 from the print media, have quit journalism in the past year. Low salaries, poor working environment, access to information are factors that demotivated the media professionalisms. In the political context the report states that the pressure the government can exert on the media is limited by the parliamentary system, which allows a degree of pluralism to be asserted. Media professionals agreed that the elected government is more open than bureaucrats when it comes to sharing information. On the legal framework, the Bhutan Infocomm and Media Authority governs the media and information while journalists have to practice ethics regulated by the body. The report further asserts that in the Economic contextprivate media houses face sustainability issue in a difficult economic environment, with a relatively low readership and insufficient advertising. “Most ads are placed by government agencies, which account for 80% of the advertising revenue of print newspapers and most of the agencies uses social media and their own official pages for passing information and advertise. The national newspaper is given highest priority for the advertisement,” it states. Further, on the sociocultural context it states that many journalists avoid covering sensitive issues for fear of appearing to challenge the social order. However, on the safety aspects, journalists in Bhutan do not face any physical threats but, as a result of social media’s development, any reporting that may cause annoyance, can be targeted in social media platforms. Nonetheless, even with the significant drop, Bhutan’s press freedom is much better in the Asian region. In the SAARC region, Nepal ranks 95, the Maldives 100, Sri Lanka 135, Pakistan 150, Afghanistan 152, India 161, and Bangladesh 163. Norway ranked first with 95.18 points followed by Ireland and Denmark with 89.91 and 89.48 points, respectively. The index was declared on 3 May by the RSF coinciding with the World Press Freedom Day. The President of the Journalist Association of Bhutan (JAB), Rinzin Wangchuk, shared that it was expected that Bhutan’s press freedom ranking would drop by few positions since access to information was restricted by some public institutions. “But we never thought that our press ranking would drop by 57. It is really a shocking news although access to information has never been as challenging as over the last few years,” the president said. In its 21st annual South Asia Press Freedom Report 2022-2023, the International Federation of Journalists (IFJ) stated that the shifting media landscape coupled with the high turnover of journalists is compounded by shrinking access to information, all of which is impacting news coverage and people’s access to information. The report was launched on 3 May coinciding with the International Press Freedom Day.",
