    "description": "Temperature readings at O’Hare International Airport hit 86 degrees Sunday.",
    "content": "Sunday was the warmest day of the year in Chicago so far, but temperatures plummeted in the evening, with a severe thunderstorm watch issued for some areas south of the city, according to the National Weather Service. Temperature readings at O’Hare International Airport hit 87 degrees Sunday, said weather service meteorologist Eric Lenning. Advertisement By about 7:30 p.m., the temperature at O’Hare had dropped to about 63 degrees, Lenning said. The weather service issued a severe thunderstorm watch for parts of Illinois and northwest Indiana until 12 a.m. Monday. Advertisement “The concern is for large hail and damaging winds as well as flash flooding,” Lenning said. On Twitter, the weather service warned of the potential for frequent lightening as well as gusts of wind that could reach up to 65 mph. A severe thunderstorm watch has been issued for parts of Illinois and Indiana until 12 AM CDT pic.twitter.com/6n346qKoip — NWS Chicago (@NWSChicago) May 7, 2023 Flash Flood Warning including Joliet IL, Kankakee IL and New Lenox IL until 10:15 PM CDT pic.twitter.com/se2QOmooN4 — NWS Chicago (@NWSChicago) May 8, 2023 A flash flood warning was issued for some areas south and west of Chicago, including Joliet and Kankakee, until 12:15 a.m. Monday. The “heaviest activity” would occur in the south suburbs, Lenning said, though Chicagoans could expect to see some rain Sunday evening. Monday was expected to bring a few lingering showers, with the rest of the week seeing highs in the upper 70s and lower 80s, with cooler temperatures along the lakeshore.",
